    "type": "article",
    "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bank_(geography)",
    "title": "Bank (geography)",
    "content": "A bank in geography refers to the sloping ground bordering a river, lake, or sea, often formed by the deposition of alluvium carried by flowing water. River banks are essential components of the fluvial system, influencing channel shape, flow velocity, and flood risk. They can be erosional (cut banks) or depositional (point bars). The stability of these banks is determined by factors like soil type, vegetation cover, and flow energy. Coastal banks, such as sandbanks or mudflats, are similarly formed by wave and tidal action, shaping shorelines and providing critical intertidal habitats. Understanding bank structure is vital for hydrology and coastal management.",
    "snippet": "In geography, a bank is a landform created by the deposition of sediment carried by a river or stream. These features are typically elongated and parallel to the direction of the current, often forming on the inside bends of meandering rivers. Banks play a crucial role in river morphology and sediment transport dynamics.",
    "created_at": "2026-01-20T19:20:22.806602Z",
